{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16441"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16441"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.08,0.17,0.08,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65487"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9132"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5115"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"10095"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22530"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65487"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcitonin is a hormone involved in calcium homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary physiological action of calcitonin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates osteoblast activity to form new bone","Increases calcium reabsorption in the kidneys","Promotes vitamin D activation in the kidneys","Increases calcium absorption from the intestine","Inhibits osteoclast activity and reduces blood calcium"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary physiological action of calcitonin is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibit osteoclast activity and reduce blood calcium\u003C/strong\u003E. It is secreted by thyroid C cells in response to elevated blood calcium levels and acts to lower calcium concentrations through two main mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInhibition of osteoclast-mediated bone resorption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreased urinary calcium excretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile calcitonin may have minor effects on osteoblasts, its main action is on osteoclasts. Therefore, the primary action of calcitonin is not to \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate osteoblast activity and form new bone. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcitonin actually increases calcium excretion by the kidneys; it does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease calcium reabsorption. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of vitamin D is promoted in the kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E by parathyroid hormone, not calcitonin.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin D, not calcitonin, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreases calcium absorption from the intestine\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcitonin is secreted by parafollicular cells (C cells) of the thyroid gland in response to elevated blood calcium levels.","Calcitonin reduces blood calcium by inhibiting osteoclast activity and promoting calcium excretion by the kidneys.","The physiological effects of calcitonin are relatively minor compared to parathyroid hormone and vitamin D."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16441"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T14:20:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T17:21:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9132"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65487"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","li